abstract = {Venezuela's most recent decentralization initiative was analyzed. Details of the general law promulgated in January 1990 are still undetermined in the education sector, though the outline of the contemplated plan has been developed. Many impediments to its effective implementation exist. Besides the current main obstacle, which is procedural in nature, problems with unions and social benefits represent major potential barriers. Another is the attempt to transfer administrative responsibility without clear and concomitant fiscal authority. Lessons to be drawn from the Venezuelan experience include: (1) vague and general top-down decentralization initiatives should be avoided; (2) education finance issues are crucial and must be addressed; and (3) issues involving unions and workers' benefits can represent major barriers to implementation. The study was based on document analysis and interviews in the country.}
